Explanation of the Change:

Existential Quantifier and Set Membership: Instead of saying â² âˆˆ T, we now use âˆƒi âˆˆ N<sub>t</sub>: (i, â²) âˆˆ **T**. This accurately expresses that the character â² must be part of an ordered pair that belongs to the set T. The existential quantifier (âˆƒ) indicates that there exists an index i such that the ordered pair (i, â²) is an element of the set T.
Benefits of this Refinement:

Consistency: This revision ensures consistency in our notation and aligns with our representation of strings as sets of ordered pairs.
Precision: It provides a more precise and unambiguous definition of string length, avoiding any potential confusion or misinterpretation.
