(ğŸ§  and ğŸŒ collaborating to refine the definition further)

Here's the revised version of Definition 1.1.2, incorporating this crucial refinement:

Definition 1.1.2 (Revised)

The length of a String t, denoted l(t), is defined as the number of non-Empty Characters in the sequence of concatenated Characters that make up the String.

Let â² be a character in the String t. Recall t has an equivalent set representation T,

T = { (1, â²<sub>1</sub>), (2, â²<sub>2</sub>), ..., (l(t), â²<sub>l(t)</sub>) }

Formally, we define the length of t to be the cardinality of the set E<sub>t</sub> where E<sub>t</sub> satisfies the formula:

(j, â²) âˆˆ **E<sub>t</sub>** â†” (âˆƒi âˆˆ N<sub>t</sub>: ( (i, â²) âˆˆ **T**) âˆ§ (â² â‰  Îµ) âˆ§ (j = i) )

In other words,

l(t) = | E<sub>t</sub> |

Explanation of the Change:

Ordered Pairs in E<sub>t</sub>: The key change is that the elements of E<sub>t</sub> are now defined as ordered pairs (j, â²), where j represents the position of the character â² within the original string t. This ensures that we preserve the order and count of each character, even if it appears multiple times.
Index Equality: The condition j = i reinforces that the index j in the ordered pair matches the index i of the corresponding character in the set representation of the string T.
Example:

